CMSC320 Final Tutorial: Predicting Stroke¶

By Tina Le¶

Introduction¶

Strokes occur when blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced. This prevents brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients and as a result, brain cells begin to die in minutes.

According to the CDC, stroke is the 5th leading cause of death in the United States. In fact, someone in the U.S. dies of stroke approximately every 4 minutes. The statistics are startling and predicting stroke can be very difficult due to many different pathophysiologies. Stroke warnings can occur hours or even days before the attack. Without urgent treatment, serious damage can occur to the brain and can result in negative repercussions.

I'm interested to see if we can utilize data science in order to investigate what factors might be related to strokes. In this tutorial, we will use data to examine the relationship between stroke and various factors like gender, age, smoking status, etc. We will try to predict strokes among patients using Machine Learning algorithms and analyze them to find which factors may have contributed to strokes. Hopefully after this tutorial, we can have a better idea of correlated causes in order to better reliably predict strokes.

Cleaning the Data¶

In order to avoid future issues with data analysis and get meaningful results, it is important that we clean the data to make sure it is tidy.

We can see already above that there are some missing values in the data set (specified by the NaN entry). Let's see how many there currently are.

There are 201 missing values in the bmi column. First, let's remove outliers. More specifically, according to an NHSN announcement, BMI values are considered outliers if they are less than 12 or greater than 60. We are going to remove this from the data set by replacing them with NaN to avoid skewed data.

In [36]:
# Replace BMI outliers with NaN
df['bmi'] = df['bmi'].apply(lambda bmi_val: bmi_val if 12 < bmi_val < 60 else np.nan)

We already saw that there were 201 missing values in the data set. Now, there are going to be additional NaN entries since we just replace BMI outliers as well. Let's see how many missing entries there are now.

For this particular data set, I am going to replace the missing values with the mean of the bmi column.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now we will perform exploratory data analysis, or EDA for short. In this stage, we try to better understand our data set, typically through data visualization, in order to look for potential trends or any strong relationships between various attributes and our target variable: stroke.

In [43]:
# Calculates correlation between numerical values in the data set.
data_corr = df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Generate correlation matrix
sns.heatmap(data_corr, annot= True)
plt.title("Correlation Between Each Attribute")
plt.show()

We have generated a correlation matrix that displays the correlation coefficients between each attribute of the data set. Boxes that are lighter in color (closer to 1.0) indicate a stronger positive correlation whereas boxes that are darker in color (closer to 0) indicate that there is less of a correlation between the two variables.

In our generated correlation matrix, we can see that most of the boxes are darker colored. We are most interested in the last row (or column) of the correlation matrix, which shows the correlation (or lackthereof) between stroke and the other dependent variables.

The orange points on the scatterplot represent when an entry in the data set is a stroke (stroke == 1). Again, we see the same result regarding age (Age 40 or above, risk of stroke increases; 60+ risk of stroke greatly increases).

Now, we can see that people with a BMI between 25+ increase their likelihood of getting a stroke. However, the scatterplot is more dense (for had_stroke) for BMI values between 25 to 35.

Overall, combining these two observations, we can assume that people ages 40+ with BMI of 25 to 35 have greater chances of getting a stroke.

Looking at the plot, it appears that there are varying average glucose levels that can lead to a stroke. In healthcare, it is known that elevated glucose levels contribute to strokes. I thought this was interesting because in the scatterplot, it seems that there is a greater number of people having average glucose levels less than 110 (lower glucose levels) that suffer from strokes. There is currently no evidence that low glucose levels trigger strokes, however, low levels do set up an environment in which, if a stroke happens, it's super-sized. Maybe the strokes with low average glucose levels in the data set are "super-sized" strokes.

Balance the data set¶

Before we can actually build a model, we have to make sure our data set is properly prepared. One of the first things I noticed about the data set was how much entries there are for no strokes (or stroke == 0). This caused the data to be imbalanced. In case you are having trouble imagining an inbalanced data set, let's plot it.

In [54]:
x_counts = df['stroke'].value_counts().index
y_counts = df['stroke'].value_counts().values

sns.barplot(x=x_counts, y=y_counts)

plt.title('Imbalanced Stroke Data Set')
plt.xlabel('Stroke')
plt.show()

As you can see, there is a much greater proportion of 'stroke == 0' values compared to 'stroke == 1' (which is what we are actually interested in). Some of the problems with unbalanced data sets are that some models are susceptible to unbalanced data sets. The algorithm might recieve too many examples from a certain class resulting in a biased model. It doesn't learn what makes the other class different and can overfit the majority class.

To balance the data set, we will be up sampling the minority class.

In [57]:
sm = SMOTE(random_state=2)
X, y = sm.fit_resample(X, y) 

# Now display the newly updated data set
sns.barplot(x=['0', '1'], y =[sum(y == 0), sum(y == 1)])
plt.title('Balanced Stroke Data Set')
plt.xlabel('Stroke')
plt.show()

It's important to note that we choose to split into Test and Train sets before balancing the data set because if we oversample first, there is a possibility that the same observations will be present in both sets. This results in overfitting and poor generalizations. Also, biased results can lead to a higher accuracy.

The first ML algorithm we performed was logistic regression. We used accuracy as a performance metric and calculated it by comparing test set values and predicted values. The logistic regression resulting in an accuracy of 95.37%, which is considered a "great" accuracy.

k-NN Classification¶

Let's try performing another ML algorithm. This time we will perform a k-NN classification, with k=5 initially.

In [71]:
# Create KNN Classifier 
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 5)

# Train the model using the training sets
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred_2 = knn.predict(X_test)

# Check accuracy 
k_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_2)
print("Accuracy: ", '%.2f'% (k_accuracy*100),"%")
# or print(knn.score(X_test, y_test))

# Performing 10-fold cross validation

# Create new KNN model
knn_cv = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 5)

# Train model with cv of 10
scores = cross_val_score(knn_cv, X, y, cv = 10)

# Print each cv score (accuracy) and average them
print(scores)
print("cv_scores mean: {}".format(np.mean(scores)))

# Using GridSearchCV in order to find optimal k value for a cv of 10

# Create new a KNN model
knn2 = KNeighborsClassifier()

# Create a dictionary of all values we want to test for n_neighbors

param_grid = {"n_neighbors": np.arange(1, 20)}

# Use gridsearch to test all values for n_neighbors

knn_gscv = GridSearchCV(knn2, param_grid, cv = 10)

# Fit model to data
knn_gscv.fit(X, y)

# Check the optimal performing n_neighbors value (k value)
print("Optimal k value: ", knn_gscv.best_params_)

# Check mean score for optimal performing value of k 
print("Mean score for optimal k value: ", knn_gscv.best_score_)

The confusion matrix represents the following:

  • Top Left -> True Negative: Correctly predicted a non-stroke
  • Top Right -> False Positive: Incorrectly predicted a non-stroke
  • Bottom Left -> False Negative: Incorrectly predicted a stroke
  • Bottom Right -> True Positive: Correctly predicted a stroke

The 2x2 table above tells us that our data is very biased towards the true negative (i.e. correctly predicting a non-stroke). This happens to be a good thing! However, there are some occurences of incorrectly predicting a stroke as well. One on end, this is a bad thing because it tells us our algorithm is not completely accurate but you can also see this as a good thing because we would rather have false negatives than false positives.

Conclusion¶

Although no in-depth statistical analysis or hypothesis testing has been performed yet, we have definitely obseved some potential trends/relationships from our data.

Here is a summary of our findings:

  1. The likelihood of getting stroke increases as you age. But the risk of stroke begins ~40 years old and greatly increases once you reach 60 and continue aging.

  2. People with BMI values ranging from 25-35 are at higher risk for encountering a stroke.

  3. Varying levels of average glucose level contribute to risk of stroke but lower levels have a higher liklihood for stroke (in this data set).

  4. Hypertension and heart disease is most likely correlated to stroke.

  5. Contrary to what is known in healthcare, this particular data set shows that smoking status does not affect your risk of getting a stroke.

  6. Gender is not a indicator of the probability of getting a stroke.

Overall, I hope you were able to learn something about data analysis, data cleaning, data visualization, or Machine Learning algorithms from this tutorial! Data science is so important and cool and allows us to leverage available data to draw conclusions that may even save lives!
